result.execSummary:
The defendant Hesham M. Al-Ali was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case. One or more other charges in this case were dismissed. The dismissed charges were not proven and have no legal effect. Hesham M. Al-Ali is presumed innocent of the dismissed charges.

  • Hesham M. Al-Ali was found guilty of WIC - Provide Cash for Drafts, a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 253.06(4)(a)2.
  • Hesham M. Al-Ali was found guilty of WIC - Provide Cash for Drafts (2nd+), a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 253.06(4)(a)2.

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Hesham M. Al-Ali in court with attorney Timothy Lloyd Baldwin.  David A. Feiss appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Deputy court clerk cmt.

AS TO COUNT 1:  Pursuant to plea negotiations and on motion of state, Court orders Count 1 Dismissed. 

AS TO COUNTS 4-9:  Pursuant to plea negotiations and on motion of state, Court orders Counts 4-9 DISMISSED and read-in for purposes of sentencing. 

AS TO COUNTS 2 and 3:  Defendant was advised of constitutional rights and maximum penalties, waived all rights, plead NO CONTEST and was examined as to the plea.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights and Addendum received and filed.  Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis for the plea.  Defendant further advised that if he is not a US citizen deportation is possible.  Court found defendant guilty as charged in the Information and ordered entry of Judgment of Conviction.  
Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon he may never possess a firearm.  Court advised defendant that his voting rights are suspended, and may not vote in any election until his civil rights are restored.
